  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The sustainability declaration is a standard Queensland government form (Form 2) that residential property sellers must complete and provide to buyers before the contract of sale is signed. It is a legal disclosure requirement under the Queensland Building and Construction Commission Act and related residential property legislation. Failing to provide it, or completing it inaccurately, creates legal exposure for sellers that can affect settlement and, in some cases, allow a buyer to terminate the contract.</p>

      <p>Despite its name, the sustainability declaration is less about environmental philosophy and more about practical disclosure of specific features of the home. Buyers use it as a factual checklist of what is and is not installed in the property. Sellers should approach it the same way: as a factual record, not an opportunity to present the property favourably.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the form covers</h2>
      <p>The sustainability declaration asks sellers to confirm whether the property has specific features across three broad categories: energy efficiency, water efficiency, and insulation.</p>

      <p>Under energy efficiency, the form asks about solar photovoltaic panels, solar hot water systems, and rainwater tanks connected to the home. Sellers must confirm whether each item is present, and if so, whether it is in working order. A solar system that is installed but not operational, or a rainwater tank that is connected but has a faulty pump, should be declared as present but not fully functional. Declaring a non-functional system as functional creates a warranty issue that can resurface at settlement.</p>

      <p>Water efficiency questions cover flow-restricting showerheads and dual-flush toilets, both of which are standard in most homes built or renovated in the past fifteen years. If your home was built earlier and has never had plumbing upgrades, check the fixtures before completing this section. Incorrect answers here are common and often create unnecessary friction in negotiations when buyers verify the declaration during their building and pest inspection.</p>

      <p>The insulation section requires sellers to confirm whether ceiling insulation is present. This is often the question vendors are least certain about, particularly in older Queenslander-style homes where insulation may have been retrofitted inconsistently or is simply unknown. If you genuinely do not know, the correct answer is to note that you are unaware rather than to guess.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When it must be provided</h2>
      <p>The sustainability declaration must be given to the buyer before the contract of sale is entered into. In practice, this means it should be prepared before your first open home and provided either as part of the contract documentation or as a standalone form given to prospective buyers on request. Your agent should have the form and should include it in the contract pack prepared by your solicitor or conveyancer.</p>

      <p>For properties sold at auction, the declaration must be available at the auction. It should be displayed at the property during the auction inspection period so that registered bidders can read it before bidding.</p>

      <p>Unlike some disclosure obligations in other states, there is no prescribed number of days before settlement by which the form must be provided. The requirement is simply that it precedes the contract. If a buyer signs a contract without having received the sustainability declaration, the seller is in breach and the buyer may have grounds to terminate. Your conveyancer will ensure the form is included in the contract documentation, but as the seller, it is your responsibility to complete it accurately in the first place.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How it differs from the Section 52 disclosure statement</h2>
      <p>The sustainability declaration is often confused with the broader disclosure obligations contained in the Property Occupations Act 2014, which require sellers to complete a separate disclosure statement addressing title encumbrances, easements, notices, and other property matters. These are two separate documents with separate requirements.</p>

      <p>The disclosure statement under Section 52 is the broader document and covers the legal and title aspects of the property: body corporate issues, outstanding notices, encumbrances, and whether the property is subject to any heritage listing or contamination register. The sustainability declaration specifically covers the physical sustainability features listed above.</p>

      <p>Sellers need to complete both. Your conveyancer will prepare the disclosure statement based on title searches and information you provide. The sustainability declaration you complete yourself, based on your knowledge of the property's physical features.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What if you cannot complete it accurately?</h2>
      <p>The most common situation where sellers struggle with the form is when they genuinely do not know the answer to a question. This comes up most often with ceiling insulation in older homes, or with solar systems that were installed by a previous owner and where the seller has limited documentation.</p>

      <p>Queensland legislation allows sellers to indicate where information is genuinely unknown. Noting that you are unaware of whether insulation is present is a legitimate response and is far preferable to guessing incorrectly. What the legislation does not allow is a seller knowingly providing false information. If a seller knows a solar system is not operational but declares it as working, that creates an actionable misrepresentation.</p>

      <p>If you are uncertain about any component of the form, speak with your conveyancer before completing it. They can advise on what level of certainty is required and how to phrase responses that reflect genuine uncertainty without creating unnecessary problems in the sale process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common questions from sellers</h2>
      <p>A question that comes up regularly is whether a seller needs to get a new form if the property's features change between listing and settlement. If, for example, a solar system that was working at the time of listing fails before settlement, the seller should notify the buyer and update the declaration. Letting a material change pass unreported creates exposure.</p>

      <p>Another common question is whether the sustainability declaration affects the sale price. In practice, the form itself rarely influences buyer decisions directly. Buyers do not pay a premium because a property has dual-flush toilets, and they do not discount heavily because it lacks solar. What the form does is set expectations. Inaccuracies that buyers discover during the inspection period create distrust that can translate into price renegotiations or cooling-off situations that have nothing to do with the items on the form and everything to do with the erosion of confidence.</p>

      <p>Complete it accurately, include it in the contract, and move on. It is a straightforward form that should take fifteen minutes for a seller who knows their property.</p>

